Serving CellxGene on a GCP Server

Kyle Kimler

How it works

We create a GCP compute instance to serve cellxgene privately to team members and collaborators. GCP compute instances can be set up to have ssh key access. By placing our h5ad files in the server and tunneling the app from the server to the user with ssh port forwarding, anyone with an ssh key to the server can view that data on cellxgene.

Server Setup

Our GCP server has the following specs:

  • n1-standard-1 (1 vCPU, 3.75 GB memory)
  • image: ubuntu-1804-bionic-v20210323

created with the command

gcloud compute instances create INSTANCENAME \
--zone us-east1-b \
--image ubuntu-1804-bionic-v20210323 \
--image-project ubuntu-os-cloud

Security settings for the server instance must be set in the console

  • Remote access set to ‘ssh’
  • firewall-rules must allow specific port forwarding for the list of ports you use below

Individual ssh keys are created per person (on their computer) using

ssh-keygen -t rsa -f ~/.ssh/INSTANCENAME_public_ssh_key -C USERNAME

Those keys are collected and added to the GCP console at: https://console.cloud.google.com/compute/metadata/sshKeys

Cellxgene

We’re currently serving cellxgene using cellxgene-gateway, developed by Novartis: https://github.com/Novartis/cellxgene-gateway

cellxgene-gateway can be served to an external host by setting some parameters in the shell. We use ssh port forwarding to send the app directly to our scientists’ laptops. That way, only people with ssh keys to the server have access to the data. For public data sharing, you can send the app to a website instead.

Cellxgene-gateway initiation

#Connect to your server through gcloud
gcloud compute ssh SERVERNAME
#or ssh to its external IP
ssh  -i ~/.ssh/vm_public_ssh_key USERNAME@my.ext.ip.adr

#Open a super-user terminal
sudo -s 

#Set server settings for cellxgene

#add cellxgene's path to $PATH (this is wherever you downloaded it, I did it on my username)
export PATH=$PATH':/home/USERNAME/.local/bin'
export CELLXGENE_LOCATION=/home/USERNAME/.local/bin/cellxgene
export CELLXGENE_DATA=/home/USERNAME/cellxgene
#Set gateway IP to VM's external IP address by querying it in VM metadata
export GATEWAY_IP=$(sudo curl -H "Metadata-Flavor: Google" http://metadata/computeMetadata/v1/instance/network-interfaces/0/access-configs/0/external-ip)
#set a specific port to forward
export GATEWAY_PORT=5000
export EXTERNAL_HOST=${GATEWAY_IP}:${GATEWAY_PORT}
#not sure if http is necessary
export EXTERNAL_PROTOCOL=http
#a major use case for us is using annotations to rapidly create cellxgene subsets
export GATEWAY_ENABLE_ANNOTATIONS=True

#Start the server
cellxgene-gateway

If you are the one running cellxgene-gateway, leave this terminal open. Open a new terminal instance to access it.

We do this by tunneling the VM’s gateway port to your computer’s localhost (aka 127.0.0.1). Doing so allows you to open cellxgene in your browser. You can read about other port forwarding methods here: https://help.ubuntu.com/community/SSH/OpenSSH/PortForwarding

Connecting to cellxgene from your computer via ssh tunneling

ssh to IP

ssh -L 5000:127.0.0.1:5000 -i ~/.ssh/INSTANCENAME_public_ssh_key USERNAME@34.74.167.35

gcloud API

gcloud compute ssh INSTANCENAME -- -L 5000:127.0.0.1:5000






Viewing cellxgene

Now you have tunneled the VM’s port 5000 to your own port 5000. Open a browser on your machine and type in the URL:

https://127.0.0.1:5000

You should see the welcome page, which looks like this:




Next, check out the File Crawler to see which datasets are currently available. If you want to only visualize the samples, click a link to the .h5ad file you’re interested in. If you’re interested in creating your own annotations or subsetting the datasets available here, click the ‘new’ button next the dataset you want to subset.

Important considerations

  • I’m not sure of the limits yet, so far I’ve found:
  • You can only visualize datasets ~ < 250k cells in size
  • multiple people can tunnel and view the app at the same time

When you push the limits, the app just crashes, you can reset it by a few ctrl+C in the terminal running the app
